  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Rank-nullity theorem for matrices</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        For each scenario use the rank-nullity theorem for matrices to compute the desired information from the given information. 
      </p>
    </introduction>
  
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>A\in M_{7\times 5}</m> and <m>\nullity A=2</m>, compute <m>\rank A</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>A\in M_{7\times 5}</m> and <m>\nullity A=2</m>, compute <m>\dim \RS A</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>A\in M_{3\times 5}</m> and <m>\CS A=\R^3</m>, compute <m>\nullity A</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>A\in M_{7\times 5}</m> and <m>\NS A=\{\boldzero\}</m>, compute <m>\dim \CS A</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercisegroup>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be <m>m\times n</m> with <m>n\lt m</m>.
        Prove that there is a
        <m>\boldb\in\R^m</m> such that the system <m>A\boldx=\boldb</m> is inconsistent.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Use <xref ref="th_col_space"/> and <xref ref="th_rank_nullity_matrix"/>.
      </p>
    </hint>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex_col_inv">
    <statement>
      <p>
        We know that in general that row equivalent matrices do not have equal column spaces, but show that this is the case if the matrices are invertible. In other words, prove that if <m>A</m> is invertible and <m>A</m> is row equivalent to <m>B</m>, then <m>\CS A=\CS B</m>. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n\times n</m> matrix.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Prove: <m>A^2=\boldzero_{n\times n}</m> if and only if <m>\CS A\subseteq \NS A</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          Construct a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix <m>A</m> with <m>\NS A=\CS A=\Span\{(1,2)\}</m>. Verify that your <m>A</m> satisfies <m>A^2=\boldzero_{2\times 2}</m>.
        </li>
      </ol>

    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>A</m> is <m>m\times n</m> with <m>m\ne n</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Prove: either the rows of <m>A</m> are linearly dependent or the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly dependent.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove: <m>\nullity A=\nullity A^T</m> if and only if <m>A</m> is a square matrix.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
